node.title: Manipulating and Analyzing Output Values of  Vectors

node.bodyText:
hello
So first, for context, are you using a single simulation to compute 3000 clusters?
Could these simulations be separated numerically using multiapps?
Secondly, are you working with vectors of material properties? Or a vector (really array, vector is size 3 only) material property?
It looks to me like the latter.
Finally,
this doesnt look right
    for (size_t j = 0; j < (*Matrix_Size_prop_old)[_qp]; j++) {        //--> Max ( (*Matrix_Size_prop_old)[_qp]= 3000)

could it be
    for (size_t j = 0; j < (*Matrix_Size_prop_old)[_qp].size(); j++) {        //--> Max ( (*Matrix_Size_prop_old)[_qp]= 3000)

?
Guillaume

Thank you for your consideration.
Regarding the vectors, they represent the number densities of various sizes of different types of precipitates. (For example, j = 50 corresponds to the number density of the precipitate phi3 phase with a specific size of 5 nm, stored in Rho_out_Vector[phi3][j],  or j = 500 represents the number density of precipitates with other sizes, such as 93 nm.) These vectors are obtained for tracking the evolution of number densities for different sizes of precipitates over time in a transient simulation.
Regarding the use of the multiapp, if there is a pre-existing transfer code designed for transferring these vectors within the simulation, it would be suitable for my needs (specifically for the next steps of my project).
Since you mentioned that only vectors can be used, I employed other material properties calculated in the input file to compute these vectors, but these vectors of material properties are utilized to return results to the input file; there are no other computations involved in this simulation.
Thank you once again for your assistance.
Sajjad

we do not have code to transfer array material properties, or maps right now.
However it s not that difficult to write new transfers that are only changing the source of the data, as long as the target (a variable) is the same.
so Rho_out_Vector[phi3][j] has two indexes, is the underlying data type a vector of vector?

Yes. it is a vector of vector, but it would be possible to change it into three separate vectors instead,
like: Phi1_Rho_out_Vector[i], Phi2_Rho_out_Vector[i], and Phi3_Rho_out_Vector[i]

That might be easier, there's a tad more capability with array material properties than with arbitrary tensors/matrix.
Still no transfer through.
I'm still pondering how to tackle this issue. Any suggestions would be greatly appreciated.
which issue in particular? the transfer/

Sending a vector of real values to the vectorpostprocessor or transfer it through a multiapp.
Thanks in advance for your consideration,
Sajjad

you cant send to a vectorpostprocessor.
You can use a VectorPostprocessor to collect data from the simulation.
Here's the full list of the ones you can use:
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/syntax/VectorPostprocessors/index.html
But here the vectors are different at each location in space right? It s like a material property?

node.title: Multiple heat sources
node.bodyText:
I want to add two heat sources at a same time to my geometry. at top I have laser and from both right and left sides I wanna apply the electric field. So currently I'm able to separately apply the laser heat source and also the joule heating effect by electric field. but I don't know how can I combine both of them as a combined heat source in my problem. here is my kernels:
# 1: thermal conduction
# rou*cp*dT/dt=grad(K)*grad(T)+qdot
[Kernels]
  #grad(K)*grad(T)
  [heat_conduction]
    type = ADHeatConduction
    variable = T
  []
  #rou*cp*dT/dt
  [time_derivative]
    type = ADHeatConductionTimeDerivative
    variable = T
  []
  # 2: laser
  #qdot
  [heat_source1]
    type = ADMatHeatSource
    material_property = volumetric_heat
    variable = T
  []
  # 3: electrical conduction
  #qdot
[heat_source2]
  type = ADJouleHeatingSource
  elec = phi
  variable = T
[]
# grad(sigma*grad(phi))
  [./electric]
    type = ADHeatConduction
    variable = phi
    thermal_conductivity = electrical_conductivity
  []
[]


and here is my error:
 Solve Did NOT Converge!
  Finished Solving                                                                       [ 24.17 s] [    0 MB]
Aborting as solve did not converge


*** ERROR ***
The following error occurred in the object "TimeStepper", of type "ConstantDT".

Solve failed and timestep already at or below dtmin, cannot continue!


I would be grateful if someone help me with this issue that how can I combine two heat sources together.

Hello
it s ok to have two kernels, once for each heat source.
The problem is likely that either:

the problem is ill posed for another reason
the numerical solver is failing to find the solution

Please see this page for more help
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/application_usage/failed_solves.html
Guillaume

    line_search = none
    nl_abs_tol = 1e-10
Isn't there a rigid body mode in the x direction or am I missing something?

          function = -100000000*t
          boundary = top
          use_automatic_differentiation = true
   []

I think you're right and there is a rigid body mode in the x-direction.

node.title: [Geochemistry Module] 2D GeoTes Simulation
node.bodyText:
Hello,
I’m trying to understand the dissolution of the QuartzLike mineral simulated in the Geochemistry module—specifically, the example on 2D GeoTes simulation. I used the following aux variable to obtain the amount (in mole) of the QuartzLike mineral that dissolves with time from the aquifer_geochemistry.i input file:
[AuxVariables]
  [diss]
    order = CONSTANT
    family = MONOMIAL
  []
[]

[AuxKernels]
  [diss]
    type = ParsedAux
    args = moles_QuartzLike
    function = 'moles_QuartzLike'
    variable = diss
  []
[]

Then I transfer it using MultiApps into the porous_flow.i file to observe how the QuartzLike mineral is dissolving with time as follows:
[AuxVariables]
  [rate] 
    order = CONSTANT
    family = MONOMIAL
  []
[]

[MultiApps]
  [react]
    type = TransientMultiApp
    input_files = aquifer_geochemistry.i
    clone_master_mesh = true
    execute_on = 'timestep_end'
  []
[]

[Transfers]
  [rate_from_geochem]
    type = MultiAppCopyTransfer
    source_variable = 'diss'
    variable = 'rate'
    from_multi_app = react
  []
[]

[Postprocessors]
  [diss_rate]
    type = PointValue
    point = '30 0 0'
    variable = rate
  []
[]


I expected the amount (in moles) of the QuartzLike mineral to decrease with time. Instead, it remains constant (with a value of 3.96e2). I’m probably missing something here. Could someone please clarify why the amount of the QuartzLike mineral isn’t decreasing? Thanks.  @WilkAndy @cpgr @GiudGiud
Ok. I’m convinced now. The mineral is dissolving at a rather slow pace. The dissolution rate gave a much clearer picture. Thanks.

node.title: Issue with hanging nodes + small strain plasticity
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I am having issues when combining hanging nodes with a small strain plasticity material. This is not with adaptivity, the mesh starts with hanging nodes and does not change.
For testing, I am running a problem in uniaxial tension. The mesh is made and refined using MOOSE.
I have the following simulation parameters:

Tensor mechanics module


Small strain + incremental formulation


volumetric locking correction
Isotropic elasticity
Power law hardening

The refined area of the mesh is designed to yield first.
I've attached the input file I used(I had to attach it as a .txt file).
tension_moose.txt
While the plastic strain field looks ok, the stress field contains significant oscillations, as seen in the image attached. These oscillations are always concentrated near the transition zones for mesh refinement.

I have tried this with several iterations on the problem setup (finite strain, no vol lock correction, total formulation) but I see the same stress oscillations each time. Also, I see no oscillations with a purely elastic material.
Any insight into this issue would be much appreciated.
@lindsayad @dschwen I think this is tied to a recent conversation.
Is there an incompatibility with how data interpolation works on hanging nodes and plasticity?
Do you see oscillations without adaptivity?
There is no adaptivity, the mesh intentionally starts with hanging nodes
But using unstructured quad mesh refinement does not lead to oscillations

Adaptivity is not used btw. It s the refineSidesetGenerator.
Does it work with a single level of refinement?
The oscillations are still present with 1 level of refinement

ok can you try with adaptivity instead of sideset refinement now?
Use a constant marker boundary-restricted to the boundary of interest
I apologize in advance if that does not work, I m trying to see if we can get your case going as our user support resources are low right now
Unfortunately, that gives similar oscillations
It seems like we should start making a list of physics that don't play well with hanging nodes :-/

What? How? How can this be physics specific? Can you show us the displacement field? Are you sure your solution is tightly converged? The residuals at the hanging nodes seem to converge from opposite signs, so a badly converged solution would exhibit exactly this checkerboarding as far as I can see.

node.title: Question about CombinerGenerator
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I am loading in two meshes and combining them into a disjoint mesh using combiner generator using the method showed below.
[Mesh]
  [refine]
    type = FileMeshGenerator
    file = '../../gold/ref_sec.msh'
  []
  [coarse]
    type = FileMeshGenerator
    file = '../../gold/coarse_sec2.msh'
  []
  [combine]
    type = CombinerGenerator
    inputs = 'coarse refine'
  []
[]

My issue is that only the subdomain ID's on the 'coarse' mesh are being preserved. The subdomains on the 'refine' mesh are being discarded by CombinerGenerator. It seems that which ever mesh is listed first in 'inputs' has its subdomain IDs preserved. I need the subdomain IDs on both meshes to be preserved. Is there a workaround for this?
edit: Note that all of the subdomainIDs between both meshes are unique

Hello
Not currently. This is a known issue, scheduled to be addressed over the summer.
For now you can either modify the generator yourself, or combine the meshes with external software first.
Guillaume

We addressed sideset IDs there #20825
For domain ids & names:
Tied to #24577
Got it, thanks!

The issue is that these two meshes doesn't have a proper block name. Can you try adding below mesh generator for each mesh and then combine? This should preserve both subdomain names
[refine_block]
   type = RenameBlockGenerator
   input = refine
   old_block = /*subdomainID here*/
   new_block = /*block name*/
 []
